\begin_layout Standard
Galaxy clusters are the most massive objects in the Universe, which provides
 extremely dense environments to galaxies and subhalos orbiting inside of
 the clusters.
 Under such environments, galaxy evolution is strongly affected by the tidal
 field such as ram-pressure stripping.
 The ram-pressure stripping removes gas from the galaxies, quenches their
 star-formation, and is considered to transform their morphologies (from
 spiral to disk) and colors (from blue to red).
 Observational evidences show that many spiral galaxies in the clusters
 have truncated gas distribution and deficient in HI gas [cite:xxx].
 A similar phenomenon is expected for subhalos in the clusters.
 In simulations, tidal forces cause mass stripping, tidal heating, and disruptio
n of subhalos inside the host halos.
 Tidal stripping also truncates their radius.
 Through the lensing studies, the truncation of the subhalos are observationally
 confirmed; Ref.
 Natarajan [xxx] shows a mass distribution for the galaxies inside the clusters
 is tidally truncated compared to the similar field galaxies.
 Besides the truncation radius, simulations show that the subhalos which
 are close to the cluster core lose more than 70% of their initial mass
 after accretion, while the subhalos at the edge of the cluster lose about
 30% of their initial mass [cite:xxx (Daisuke)].
 This is consistent with the observational study using the lensing that
 the subhalo masses and mass-to-light ratios depend on the distance from
 the cluster center and decrease toward the center [Ref:xxx (Subaru)].
\end_layout

