\begin_layout Standard
Halo assembly bias is a phenomenon that the clustering of halos exhibits
 a dependence on additional properties beyond their mass.
 In terms of the peak-background split theorem, the peaks of the same height
 in the initial density fluctuation collapse into the halos of the same
 mass; those peaks can be in different environments (i.e., having different
 peak curvature) and therefore have different assembly histories and clustering.
 This environmental difference results in the difference in the structural
 properties/internal structures of halos [cite:xxx].
 This also affects the radial distribution of subhalos; subhalos which are
 accreted earlier tend to be more centrally concentrated, and those subhalos
 also experience more mass loss due to tidal field [cite:xxx].
 We revisits the manifestation of assembly history on the internal structure
 of the clusters, using the tidal mass loss as an indicator of assembly
 time.
\end_layout

