\begin_layout Standard

\color red
The same group also measure the splashb
\color inherit
ack radius for the same samples and show the correlation between assembly
 bias and splashback radius.
 Splashback radius is a physical boundary for dark matter halos associated
 with the density caustics, which corresponds to the radius of the first
 turn-around for the accreted dark matter particles.
 While the virial radius depends only on its halo mass, the splashback radius
 depends on the accretion rate besides the mass; the larger accretion rate
 corresponds to the smaller splashback radius.
 Using the splashback radius as the radius of the halos may change the classific
ation of halos into host/sub-halos.
 Some of the host halos around more massive halos can be possibly considered
 as subhalos.
 The most possible candidates for such host halos are ejected halos, which
 are identified as host halos at present time but were subhalos in the past.
 Those ejected halos tend to exist around more massive halos.
 Ref.
 xxx[Wetzel] shows that the ejected halos more likely to host satellite
 galaxies.
 Treating ejected halos as host halos or subhalos changes the clustering
 signal on small scales.
 In this study, we also compare the clustering of subhalos on small scales
 with and without the ejected halos.
\end_layout

