\begin_layout Standard
Tidal stripping is a phenomenon that the subhalos experience mass loss due
 to tidal forces of their host halos.
 The tidal radius, which is a radius that binding energy of DM particles
 in the subhalos and tidal force are in equal, is roughly proportional to
 
\begin_inset Formula $(M_{{\rm sub}}/M_{{\rm host}})^{1/2}R$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $M_{{\rm sub}}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $M_{{\rm host}}$
\end_inset

 are the virial mass of subhalos and host halos respectively and 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 is the distance between the subhalos and the host halos.
 As a general trend, subhalos with low concentration tend to be disrupted
 more easily (cite:xxx).
 [Also, add more explanation from Frank's textbook, may mention a little
